\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 invariant Potential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One unsolved problem of the model in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chen:2014wiw"

\end_inset

 is about the vacuum alignments of familon fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, which transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{3}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{PSL}_{2}\left(7\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the model, we assumed the familon vacuum to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \bar{\varphi}\right\rangle =\left\langle \bar{\varphi}_{3}\right\rangle \begin{pmatrix}\bar{\alpha}\lambda^{8}\\
\lambda^{4}\\
1
\end{pmatrix},\quad\left\langle \bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right\rangle =\left\langle \bar{\varphi}_{3}^{\prime}\right\rangle \begin{pmatrix}\bar{\alpha}^{\prime}\lambda^{8}\\
\lambda^{4}\\
1
\end{pmatrix},\label{eq:Intro-vacuum-alignment}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}\bar{\alpha}^{\prime}=-\left(\bar{\alpha}+\bar{\alpha}^{\prime}\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
 How to build a potential that can produce vacuum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Intro-vacuum-alignment"

\end_inset

? One strategy is to build the potential perturbatively: find a potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 to produce the leading order vacuum
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \bar{\varphi}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
v
\end{pmatrix},\quad\left\langle \bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
v^{\prime}
\end{pmatrix},\label{eq:Leading-vevs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}+V_{1}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{4}$
\end_inset

 order, and finally 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}+V_{1}+V_{2}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{8}$
\end_inset

 order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we try to generate the desired vacuum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Intro-vacuum-alignment"

\end_inset

 from a renormalisable 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 invariant potential.
 We first seek for a potential for the leading order vacuum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Leading-vevs"

\end_inset

.
 We shall see that, with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, it is unable to build a renormalisable potential producing the desired
 vacuum.
 We therefore introduce an extra field for the potential.
 It turns out that, if the extra field transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

, there exists such a renormalisable potential that can produce vacuum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Leading-vevs"

\end_inset

.
 Based on the leading order potential, we then seek for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{4}$
\end_inset

 order potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the rest of this paper, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and its complex conjugate 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 are parametrized as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\varphi}=\begin{pmatrix}\bar{\varphi}_{1}\\
\bar{\varphi}_{2}\\
\bar{\varphi}_{3}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\varphi=\begin{pmatrix}\varphi_{1}\\
\varphi_{2}\\
\varphi_{3}
\end{pmatrix},\label{eq:phi-parameterize}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and similar expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Potential with one triplet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first consider the simplest case that the potential is built out of only
 one triplet.
 With only 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, we have two independent real invariants
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1},
\]

\end_inset

 and two complex invariants 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6},\quad\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}}{6}
\]

\end_inset

 which are conjugates to each other.
 The general potential therefore has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)=m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}-\left(\kappa_{1}\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}+\kappa_{1}^{*}\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}}{6}\right)+\kappa\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 are real, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 is complex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}$
\end_inset

 are invariant under a 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 transformation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the vacuum alignment of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 only depends on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 terms.
 For any nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

, one can always absorb the phase of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 into the field without changing 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 by the 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 transformation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\to e^{i\frac{\arg\kappa_{1}}{4}}\varphi,\quad\bar{\varphi}\to e^{-i\frac{\arg\kappa_{1}}{4}}\bar{\varphi},\quad\kappa_{1}\to\left|\kappa_{1}\right|,\quad\kappa_{1}^{*}\to\left|\kappa_{1}\right|
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\arg\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the phase of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We can therefore assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 is real and positive without loss of generality.
 Then the vacuum alignment of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

, if exists, is in the direction where the real part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}$
\end_inset

 is maximized.
 From the expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\left(\varphi_{1}\varphi_{2}^{3}+\varphi_{2}\varphi_{3}^{3}+\varphi_{3}\varphi_{1}^{3}\right),
\]

\end_inset

 we see that, if each 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi_{i}\right|$
\end_inset

 is fixed, the real part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}$
\end_inset

 is maximized when all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are real and have the same sign.
 We therefore limit all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 to be real and positive.
 To find the vacuum alignment of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

, we then only need to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 that maximize the real function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\varphi,\lambda\right)=\varphi_{1}\varphi_{2}^{3}+\varphi_{2}\varphi_{3}^{3}+\varphi_{3}\varphi_{1}^{3}+\lambda\left(\varphi_{1}^{2}+\varphi_{2}^{2}+\varphi_{3}^{2}-1\right).\label{eq:one-varphi-lagrange-multiplier}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the method of Lagrange multiplier, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\varphi,\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 are maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\left\langle \varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 lies along one of the four directions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\begin{pmatrix}1\\
1\\
1
\end{pmatrix},\quad\frac{4}{\sqrt{21}}\begin{pmatrix}\sin^{2}\frac{\pi}{7}\\
\sin^{2}\frac{2\pi}{7}\\
\sin^{2}\frac{3\pi}{7}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\frac{4}{\sqrt{21}}\begin{pmatrix}\sin^{2}\frac{2\pi}{7}\\
\sin^{2}\frac{3\pi}{7}\\
\sin^{2}\frac{\pi}{7}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\frac{4}{\sqrt{21}}\begin{pmatrix}\sin^{2}\frac{3\pi}{7}\\
\sin^{2}\frac{\pi}{7}\\
\sin^{2}\frac{2\pi}{7}
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:one-varphi-real-vev}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that the maximum of the real part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\Big|_{\varphi=\left\langle \varphi\right\rangle }=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}f\left(\left\langle \varphi\right\rangle ,0\right)=\frac{2}{3\sqrt{3}}.
\]

\end_inset

 The vacuum alignments of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 are the same as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:one-varphi-real-vev"

\end_inset

 up to a phase difference at each component.
 Finally, the constraints that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 should be bounded from below and that it has no local minimum at origin
 yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa>\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\left|\kappa_{1}\right|,\quad m^{2}<0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, the vacuum alignments of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 invariant potential are as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:one-varphi-real-vev"

\end_inset

.
 None of the directions lead to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 vacuum alignment.
 To produce the desired vacuum alignment, we need to build a potential with
 more fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:PSL27-Invariant-Potential"

\end_inset

Potential with two triplets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, we showed that it is impossible produce the desired
 vacuum with only one triplet.
 Now let us consider the case of two triplets.
 We first seek for a 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 invariant potential satisfying the following conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The potential is built out of two familon fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The potential is renormalisable.
 It implies that quartic invariants are the highest order invariants in
 the potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The potential only contains real invariants.
 Particularly, no cubic term is allowed in the potential.
 This will make the calculation much simpler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall show that under above assumptions, it is impossible to produce
 the desired vacuum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Leading-vevs"

\end_inset

.
 We then briefly discuss the potential with complex invariants, which cannot
 produce the desired vacuum either.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first list the possible real 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 invariants built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are two real quadratic invariants 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:app-psl27-invariants"

\end_inset

 for detailed expression of all the invariants involved in the main text.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

 denotes 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 covariant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are two types of manifestly real quartic invariants.
 The first type invariants are comprised of only one field: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8},\quad\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}}{6},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 indicates two covariants coupling as an invariant.
 Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, we obtain another three invariants.
 The second type invariants mix up the two fields: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{\bar{3}}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{3},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}}{8},\quad\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{6}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not all these quartic invariants are independent: all of them can be written
 as liner combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)\equiv\bar{\varphi}_{1}\varphi_{1}+\bar{\varphi}_{2}\varphi_{2}+\bar{\varphi}_{3}\varphi_{3}=\sqrt{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)=\bar{\varphi}_{1}\varphi_{1}^{\prime}+\bar{\varphi}_{2}\varphi_{2}^{\prime}+\bar{\varphi}_{3}\varphi_{3}^{\prime}.
\]

\end_inset

 Explicitly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1} & =\frac{1}{3}\left[D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)\right]^{2},\\
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8} & =\frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}}\left[D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)\right]^{2},\\
\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}}{6} & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\left[D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)\right]^{2},\\
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1} & =\frac{1}{3}D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right),\\
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}}{1} & =\frac{1}{3}\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2},\\
\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{\bar{3}}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{3} & =\frac{1}{2\sqrt{3}}\left(D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)-\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}\right),\\
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8} & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(2\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}-D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right),\\
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}}{8} & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(2D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)-\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}\right),\\
\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{6} & =\frac{1}{4\sqrt{6}}\left(D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)+\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that there exist only two independent quartic invariants built
 out of one triplet and two independent quartic invariants built out of
 two triplets.
 Without loss of generality, we can therefore choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}$
\end_inset

, 
