Then the general form of the potential reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)=m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+m^{\prime2}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\kappa\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\\
+\kappa^{\prime}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\xi_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\xi_{2}\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{6},\label{eq:PSL27-Potential}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 where all the coefficients are real.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 has global 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 are comprised of 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

, and their products.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 is invariant under any 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 would have 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)\times U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero, the symmetry is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 because the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 term has only 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry.
 Such a symmetry makes it impossible to single out the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 direction, as one can always rotate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 to any other direction by a 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 transformation without changing the potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's analyze the familon vacuum alignments generated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PSL27-Potential"

\end_inset

 in more details.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)$
\end_inset

 is invariant for any direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, without affecting the vacuum alignments, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 is minimized at 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\bar{\varphi}\right)=v^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)=v^{\prime2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the vacuum alignments are only determined by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

 term.
 There are three cases: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}>0$
\end_inset

, the minimum of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 is along the direction in which 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 but doesn't force 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to be parallel.
 It can be achieved, for example, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}=v\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}=v^{\prime}\left(0,1,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 is minimized if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is maximized, which occurs when 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 are parallel.
 It means that the vacuum alignments can be in any direction as long as
 they are parallel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 is invariant for any direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, none of the three cases singles out the desired vacuum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For potential with complex invariants, it can be shown that it cannot produce
 the desired vacuum either.
 There are five complex quartic invariants, all of which are listed in Appendix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:app-psl27-invariants"

\end_inset

.
 The complex part of the general potential is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
V^{\left(c\right)}\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)=m_{12}^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\xi_{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\xi_{4}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\xi_{5}\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\\
+\xi_{6}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\varphi^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\varphi^{\prime}}{6}+\xi_{7}\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{6}+\xi_{8}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\varphi^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{6}+\xi_{9}\covp{\varphi\varphi}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\varphi^{\prime}}{6}+\mathrm{c.c.}
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

 where all the coefficients are complex.
 Among these terms, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{12}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{3}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{4}$
\end_inset

 terms have the same 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|E\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right)\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 therefore cannot single out the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 direction.
 The rest terms are not 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 invariant but all vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

, and hence cannot produce extremum at the desired vacuum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, we cannot build a renormalisable potential that can generate the desired
 vacuum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Potential with an Extra Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now introduce an extra field to the potential.
 With one more field, the potential could contain more terms.
 In addition to assuming the potential to be real and renormalisable, we
 might drop some terms out if necessary for simplicity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle, the extra field can be in any representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

.
 We go through all the possible representations of the extra field and only
 find a solution when the extra field transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we do not explore the most general potential, it does not mean that
 there is no solution for other representations, but means that the simplest
 potential meeting the requirements is built out of a septet and two triplets
 fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following subsections, we first discuss the potential built out of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}\sim\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

 and one extra field, then the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi},\,\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\sim\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

 and one extra field.
 The results of the former will help us in the discussion of the latter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:one-triplet"

\end_inset

One-Triplet Case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we first discuss the case that the extra field transforms
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}$
\end_inset

, then summarize the results of other representations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first consider the invariants built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}\sim\rep{7}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}\sim\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 The decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}$
\end_inset

 representation into the subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{7}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}=\rep{1}+\rep{3}+\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is therefore convenient to express 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 and its complex conjugate as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{7}=\begin{pmatrix}s\\
\phi\\
\bar{\chi}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\bar{S}_{7}=\begin{pmatrix}\bar{s}\\
\chi\\
\bar{\phi}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{3}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{7}$
\end_inset

 and their complex conjugates, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\phi}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\chi}$
\end_inset

 transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Note that, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}$
\end_inset

 is a real representation, both 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}_{7}$
\end_inset

 transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{7}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With only 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}_{7}$
\end_inset

, we can build one quadratic invariant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}$
\end_inset

, and seven independent real quartic invariants,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1},\quad\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{6_{1}}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{6_{1}},\quad\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{6_{2}}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{6_{2}},\quad\quad\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{6_{1}}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{6_{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{7_{s}}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{7_{s}}\quad\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{7_{a}}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{7_{a}},\quad\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{7_{s}}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{7_{a}}.
\]

\end_inset

The general potential should include all these quartic invariants.
 For simplicity we only pick one invariant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}$
\end_inset

, to be contained in the potential.
 For mixing couplings between 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, we have three independent real quartic invariants, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{s}},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{a}}.
\]

\end_inset

Finally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 couplings, only one quadratic invariant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}$
\end_inset

, and one quartic invariant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}$
\end_inset

, are involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The potential consisting of these invariants reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
V\left(\bar{\varphi},S_{7}\right)=m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+m_{7}^{2}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}+\kappa_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+\zeta_{1}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\\
+\eta_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}+\eta_{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{s}}+\eta_{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{a}},\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-V}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 where all the coefficients are real.
 We will refer to this potential as one-triplet potential in the rest of
 the paper.
 We require that the potential produces the vacuum expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \bar{\varphi}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
v
\end{pmatrix},\quad\left\langle S_{7}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}\left\langle s\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle 
\end{pmatrix},\quad\text{with }\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}v_{7}\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-vev}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We choose such a vev for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 because it is the simplest case that can produce the desired familon vacuum.
 Equivalently, one can also choose the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 vev to be along 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 direction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 are treated equally in the potential.
 Other than these two choices, it cannot lead to the desired vevs based
 on our calculation.
 The potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-V"

\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)\times U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry: it is invariant under overall phase changes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{7}$
\end_inset

 to be real and positive without loss of generality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us find the constraints on the coefficients of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 First of all, there are two trivial constraints.
 The potential need to be bounded from below and does not have local minimum
 at the origin.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{1}>0,\quad\zeta_{1}>0,\quad m^{2}<0,\quad m_{7}^{2}<0.\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-trivial-constr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Constraints 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-trivial-constr"

\end_inset

 are necessary but insufficient conditions for the potential to be bounded
 from below.
 While we do not consider the exact condition, it can be satisfied when
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{1}$
\end_inset

 are positive and large enough.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then find the critical point of the potential.
 The first derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with respect its variables at the desired vacuum yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\bar{\varphi}_{3}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{v}{84}\left[56\kappa_{1}v^{2}+28\sqrt{3}m^{2}+\sqrt{21}v_{7}^{2}\left(4\eta_{1}-3\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right)\right],\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-critical1}\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\bar{\chi}_{1}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{v_{7}}{84}\left[24\zeta_{1}v_{7}^{2}+12\sqrt{7}m_{7}^{2}+\sqrt{21}v^{2}\left(4\eta_{1}-3\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right)\right],\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-critical2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 and all the others vanish.
 Here, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdots\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to indicate the expression being evaluated at the desired vacuum.
 The vanishing of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-critical1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-critical2"

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
m^{2} & =-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\kappa_{1}v^{2}-\frac{1}{4\sqrt{7}}v_{7}^{2}\left(4\eta_{1}-3\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right),\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-m2}\\
m_{7}^{2} & =-\frac{2}{\sqrt{7}}\zeta_{1}v_{7}^{2}-\frac{1}{4\sqrt{3}}v^{2}\left(4\eta_{1}-3\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right).\label{eq:S7-potential-one-filed-m72}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Substituting Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-m2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-filed-m72"

\end_inset

 into last two inequalities of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-trivial-constr"

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\kappa_{1} & >-\frac{1}{8}\sqrt{\frac{3}{7}}\frac{v_{7}^{2}}{v^{2}}\left(4\eta_{1}-3\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right),\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol4}\\
\zeta_{1} & >-\frac{1}{8}\sqrt{\frac{7}{3}}\frac{v^{2}}{v_{7}^{2}}\left(4\eta_{1}-3\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right).\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol5}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The critical point is a local minimum only if the Hessian matrix of the
 potential at the critical point is positive definite, i.e., all the eigenvalues
 of the matrix is positive.
 The Hessian matrix is a matrix of second order derivatives with respect
 to real variables.
 A tedious calculation shows that the Hessian matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 at the critical point is positive definite under the following constraints:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\eta_{2}<0,\quad\eta_{3}+\eta_{2} & >0,\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol1}\\
3\eta_{3}^{3}+\eta_{2}\eta_{3}^{2}-19\eta_{2}^{2}\eta_{3}-\eta_{2}^{3} & >0,\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol2}\\
\kappa_{1}\zeta_{1}-\frac{1}{64}\left(4\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}-3\eta_{3}\right)^{2} & >0.\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol3}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The details of the calculation is shown in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:app-one-field-hessian"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-m2"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol3"

\end_inset

 are the constraints for the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 generating the desired vevs.
 By numerical computation, we can write constraints 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol2"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{3}>-2.383\eta_{2}>0,\label{eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which will be used in the two-triplet potential case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

 symmetry of the potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-V"

\end_inset

, we can obtain vevs along other direction for free by acting on vev 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-vev"

\end_inset

 with members of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

.
 A trivial 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{3}$
\end_inset

 transformation yields a familon vev along 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1,0\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 direction.
 A nontrivial transformation can produce a familon vev along 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2}{\sqrt{7}}\begin{pmatrix}\cos\frac{\pi}{14}\\
\cos\frac{3\pi}{14}\\
\cos\frac{5\pi}{14}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

 direction up to a phase difference on each component.
 It implies that the triplet vev is not necessary along 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is noteworthy that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}_{7}$
\end_inset

 are identical if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\chi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is real.
 In such a case, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 can be represented by seven real numbers and the group generators become
 real matrices.
 This is a feature of any real representation.
 It follows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{3}$
\end_inset

 term of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 would vanish.
 Based on our calculation, such a potential is not capable of generating
 the desired familon vacuum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We performed the similar calculation for the cases in which the extra field
 transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{6}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{8}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that none of these cases leads to the desired familon vevs.
 The results are summarized as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The extra field is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\sim\rep{3}$
\end_inset

.
 To build real invariants, we need both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and its complex conjugate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\phi}\sim\rep{\bar{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 The renormalisable potential consists of real invariants is the same as
 potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PSL27-Potential"

\end_inset

 except for replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 As we have shown in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PSL27-Invariant-Potential"

\end_inset

, it is impossible to produce the desired vevs with only two triplets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The extra field transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{6}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

.
 The field, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, and its complex conjugate can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma=\begin{pmatrix}\phi\\
\bar{\chi}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\bar{\Sigma}=\begin{pmatrix}\chi\\
\bar{\phi}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{7}$
\end_inset

.
 To build the potential, we use the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 couplings as the potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-V"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 couplings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-V"

\end_inset

 are replaced by similar couplings built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{7}^{2}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\to m_{6}^{2}\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1},\quad\zeta_{1}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\to\zeta_{1}\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}.
\]

\end_inset

For mixing couplings between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 fields, there exist only three independent real renormalisable invariants:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{8_{s}},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{8_{a}}.
\]

\end_inset

With these invariants, we build a potential as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
V\left(\bar{\varphi},\Sigma\right)=m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+m_{6}^{2}\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}+\kappa_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+\zeta_{1}\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}\\
+\eta_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}+\eta_{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{8_{s}}+\eta_{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{8_{a}}.
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

We choose the vev of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \Sigma\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}\left\langle \phi\right\rangle \\
\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle =0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 along one of the three directions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =v_{6}\left(1,0,0\right),\quad\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =v_{6}\left(0,1,0\right),\quad\text{or }\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =v_{6}\left(0,0,1\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are treated equally in 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\Sigma\right)$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 cases are equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 cases.
 Because of the extra 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)\times U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry of the potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{6}$
\end_inset

 can be chosen to be real and positive.
 Our calculation shows that none of the three choices leads to the desired
 familon vevs.
 In the case of real 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 field, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\chi$
\end_inset

, we followed the similar procedure and failed to find a solution either.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The extra field transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{8}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\group$
\end_inset

.
 The field, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, and its complex conjugate can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta=\begin{pmatrix}s_{1}\\
\bar{s}_{2}\\
\phi\\
\bar{\chi}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\bar{\Delta}=\begin{pmatrix}s_{2}\\
\bar{s}_{1}\\
\chi\\
\bar{\phi}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

 transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{1^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{7}$
\end_inset

 and their complex conjugate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 transform as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{\bar{1}^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 are triplet in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{7}$
\end_inset

.
 To build the potential, we use the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 couplings as the potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-V"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 couplings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-V"

\end_inset

 are replaced by similar couplings built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{7}^{2}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\to m_{8}^{2}\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1},\quad\zeta_{1}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\to\zeta_{1}\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}.
\]

\end_inset

There are four independent real mixing couplings between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 fields: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{8_{s1}},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{8_{s2}},\quad\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{8_{a}}.
\]

\end_inset

The general potential built out of these invariants is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
V\left(\bar{\varphi},\Delta\right)=m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+m_{8}^{2}\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}+\kappa_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+\zeta_{1}\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}\\
+\eta_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}+\eta_{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{8_{s1}}+\eta_{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{8_{s1}}+\eta_{4}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{8_{a}}.
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\Delta\bar{\Delta}}{1}$
\end_inset

 is invariant for any direction of the vevs, we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 for simplicity.
 We choose the vev of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 to be one of the four cases: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \Delta\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}\left\langle s_{1}\right\rangle =v_{8}\\
\left\langle \bar{s}_{2}\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle =0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \Delta\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}\left\langle s_{1}\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \bar{s}_{2}\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle \\
\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle =0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 being along one of the three directions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =v_{8}\left(1,0,0\right),\quad\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =v_{8}\left(0,1,0\right),\quad\text{or }\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =v_{8}\left(0,0,1\right).
\]

\end_inset

 It is not necessary to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle s_{2}\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 cases since they are equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle s_{1}\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 cases.
 It turns out that none of these four cases is capable of producing the
 desired familon vev.
 In the case of real 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 field, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\chi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=s_{2}$
\end_inset

, we followed the similar procedure and failed to find a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next subsection, we will discuss the potential built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and one extra field.
 Given the results above, we will only consider the case that the extra
 field is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}\sim\rep{7}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two-Triplet Case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two-triplet potential can be obtained by combining two copies of the
 one-triplet potential plus mixing terms between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 As we have seen from the previous subsection, the one-triplet potential
 could produce multiple vevs along different directions.
 The responsibility of the mixing terms is to make two triplet vevs parallel.
 The simplest mixing term satisfying such requirement is 
\begin_inset Formula $\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}}{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity we do not consider other mixing terms.
 We also drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 term in the two-triplet potential as it is allowed to be absent from the
 results of Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:one-triplet"

\end_inset

.
 So the two-triplet potential reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)=m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+m^{\prime2}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+m_{7}^{2}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}+\xi_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}}{1}\\
+\kappa_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+\kappa_{1}^{\prime}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\zeta_{1}\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{1}\\
+\eta_{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{s}}+\eta_{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{a}}\\
+\eta_{2}^{\prime}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{s}}+\eta_{3}^{\prime}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}\bar{S}_{7}}{8_{a}},\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-V}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 where all coefficients are real.
 We require the potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-V"

\end_inset

 to produce the vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\varphi}=\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
v
\end{pmatrix},\quad\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}=\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
v^{\prime}
\end{pmatrix},\quad\left\langle S_{7}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}\left\langle s\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle 
\end{pmatrix},\quad\text{with }\;\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}v_{7}\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix},\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-vev}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle S_{7}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is chosen to be the same as the one of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-vev"

\end_inset

.
 The potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-V"

\end_inset

 is invariant under any overall phase changes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

.
 It implies that we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 to be real and positive without loss of generality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We immediately have some trivial constraints.
 As discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PSL27-Invariant-Potential"

\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}$
\end_inset

 term is maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 are parallel.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}$
\end_inset

 must be negative for producing parallel 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 vevs as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-vev"

\end_inset

.
 Further more, we have the constraints that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 should be bounded from below and not have local minimum at origin.
 Putting these together, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\kappa_{1} & >0,\quad\kappa_{1}^{\prime}>0,\quad\zeta_{1}>0,\\
m^{2} & <0,\quad m^{\prime2}<0,\quad m_{7}^{2}<0,\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-ineq-m2}\\
\xi_{1} & <0.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us find the constraints of critical point.
 The derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect its variables at the desired vacuum are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\varphi_{3}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{v}{84}\left(56\kappa_{1}v^{2}+28\xi_{1}v^{\prime2}+28\sqrt{3}m^{2}+\sqrt{21}v_{7}^{2}\eta_{2}-3\sqrt{21}v_{7}^{2}\eta_{3}\right),\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\varphi_{3}^{\prime}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{v^{\prime}}{84}\left(56\kappa_{2}v^{\prime2}+28\xi_{1}v^{2}+28\sqrt{3}m^{\prime2}+\sqrt{21}v_{7}^{2}\eta_{2}^{\prime}-3\sqrt{21}v_{7}^{2}\eta_{3}^{\prime}\right),\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\bar{\chi}_{1}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{v_{7}}{84}\left(24\zeta_{1}v_{7}^{2}+12\sqrt{7}m_{7}^{2}+\sqrt{21}(v^{2}(\eta_{2}-3\eta_{3})+v^{\prime2}(\eta_{2}^{\prime}-3\eta_{3}^{\prime}))\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 and all the others vanish.
 The vanishing of these derivatives yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
m^{2} & =-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\kappa_{1}v^{2}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\xi_{1}v^{\prime2}+\frac{1}{4\sqrt{7}}\left(3\eta_{3}-\eta_{2}\right)v_{7}^{2},\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-m2}\\
m^{\prime2} & =-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\kappa_{1}^{\prime}v^{\prime2}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\xi_{1}v^{2}+\frac{1}{4\sqrt{7}}\left(3\eta_{3}^{\prime}-\eta_{2}^{\prime}\right)v_{7}^{2},\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-mp2}\\
m_{7}^{2} & =-\frac{2}{\sqrt{7}}\zeta_{1}v_{7}^{2}+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\left(\eta_{3}v^{2}+\eta_{3}^{\prime}v^{\prime2}\right)-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{12}\left(\eta_{2}v^{2}+\eta_{2}^{\prime}v^{\prime2}\right).\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-m72}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Substituting Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-m2"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-mp2"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-m72"

\end_inset

 into inequality 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-ineq-m2"

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\kappa_{1} & >-\frac{\xi_{1}}{2}\frac{v^{\prime2}}{v^{2}}+\frac{\sqrt{21}}{56}\frac{v_{7}^{2}}{v^{2}}\left(3\eta_{3}-\eta_{2}\right),\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-k1}\\
\kappa_{1}^{\prime} & >-\frac{\xi_{1}}{2}\frac{v^{2}}{v^{\prime2}}+\frac{\sqrt{21}}{56}\frac{v_{7}^{2}}{v^{\prime2}}\left(3\eta_{3}^{\prime}-\eta_{2}^{\prime}\right),\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-kp1}\\
\zeta_{1} & >\frac{\sqrt{21}}{24}\frac{v^{2}}{v_{7}^{2}}\left(3\eta_{3}-\eta_{2}\right)+\frac{\sqrt{21}}{24}\frac{v^{\prime2}}{v_{7}^{2}}\left(3\eta_{3}^{\prime}-\eta_{2}^{\prime}\right).\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-zeta1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the constraints of the Hessian matrix, it is difficult to reduce the
 constraints exactly.
 So we try to find only sufficient constraints under which the Hessian matrix
 is positive definite.
 Based on the result 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-one-field-sol6"

\end_inset

 of the one-triplet case, we guess that the following constraints can meet
 the requirements: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{2}<0,\quad\eta_{2}^{\prime}<0,\quad\eta_{3}\geq-3\eta_{2},\quad\eta_{3}^{\prime}\geq-3\eta_{2}^{\prime},\quad\xi_{1}<0.\label{eq:S7-potential-two-field-eta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 By tedious calculation, we find that constraints 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-eta"

\end_inset

 do lead to positive definite Hessian matrix at the desired vacuum.
 The detailed calculation is shown in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:app-two-field-hessian"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, under the constraints 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-m2"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-eta"

\end_inset

, the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 shown as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-V"

\end_inset

 can produce the desired familon vacua as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-vev"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 has three independent 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetries: three global phase transformations on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 But we can reduce the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry to two by adding to 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 complex invariants without spoiling the vacuum alignments.
 Consider terms as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi_{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}+\mathrm{c.c.}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}<0$
\end_inset

 is real.
 If the norms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 are fixed, such terms are minimized when 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 are parallel and have the same phase at each component.
 Therefore, it can explicitly break one 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry without affecting the desired vacuum alignments.
 However, there are still two 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetries left over.
 Another way to eliminate the 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetries is to introduce complex invariants in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{4}$
\end_inset

 order potential, which we shall see in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{4}$
\end_inset

 order vacuum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we seek for a potential generating the desired vacuum up
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{4}$
\end_inset

 order
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \bar{\varphi}\right\rangle =v\begin{pmatrix}0\\
\lambda^{4}\\
1
\end{pmatrix},\quad\left\langle \bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\right\rangle =v^{\prime}\begin{pmatrix}0\\
\lambda^{4}\\
1
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:l4-vev}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We shall build the potential by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{4}\right)$
\end_inset

 terms to the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-V"

\end_inset

, the coefficients of which are constrained by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-m2"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-eta"

\end_inset

).
 We therefore require the vacuum of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 to be the same as vacuum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-vev"

\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle S_{7}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}\left\langle s\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \phi\right\rangle =0\\
\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle 
\end{pmatrix},\quad\text{with }\;\left\langle \bar{\chi}\right\rangle =\begin{pmatrix}v_{7}\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:l4-vev-S7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider the first derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to its variables at vacua 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:l4-vev"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:l4-vev-S7"

\end_inset

.
 We find that all the derivatives vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 order and, at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{4}\right)$
\end_inset

 order, the nonzero ones are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\varphi_{2}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{\lambda^{4}}{\sqrt{21}}vv_{7}^{2}\left(-\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right),\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\varphi_{2}^{\prime}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{\lambda^{4}}{\sqrt{21}}v^{\prime}v_{7}^{2}\left(-\eta_{2}^{\prime}+\eta_{3}^{\prime}\right),\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\phi_{1}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{\lambda^{4}v_{7}}{2\sqrt{21}}\left(2\eta_{2}v^{2}+2\eta_{2}^{\prime}v^{\prime2}\right),\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\phi_{3}}\right\rangle  & =-\frac{\lambda^{4}v_{7}}{2\sqrt{21}}\left[v^{2}\left(\eta_{2}+\eta_{3}\right)+v^{\prime2}\left(\eta_{2}^{\prime}+\eta_{3}\right)\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset

To have extremum at the vacua, we need to cancel these derivatives by adding
 to the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{4}\right)$
\end_inset

 terms.
 It turns out that, with only real invariants, one cannot find such terms.
 We therefore consider complex invariants.
 By enumerating invariants built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

, we found a potential as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{1}=\lambda^{4}\left(c_{1}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}S_{7}}{8_{s}}+c_{2}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{8}\cdot\covp{S_{7}S_{7}}{8_{s}}+c_{3}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1}\cdot\covp{S_{7}S_{7}}{1}+c_{4}\covp{\bar{\varphi}S_{7}}{7}\cdot\covp{S_{7}S_{7}}{7_{s}}+\mathrm{c.c.}\right),\label{eq:l4-V1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 are real constants.
 The expaned expression of each invariant is listed in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:app-psl27-invariants"

\end_inset

.
 The form of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not unique.
 There are other forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the requirment and we simply choose one that is convenient for
 calculation.
 We stress that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 breaks the three 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetries of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:S7-potential-two-field-V"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not invariant under an overall phase change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After adding 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bar{\varphi},\bar{\varphi}^{\prime},S_{7}\right)$
\end_inset

