\begin_layout Standard
Now let us impose supersymmetry to the model.
 Firstly, we note that there is no cubic invariant built out of two triplets.
 We therefore need to introduce extra fields.
 From the Kronecker product 
\begin_inset Formula $\rep{\bar{3}}+\rep{\bar{3}}=\rep{6}_{s}+\rep{3}_{a}$
\end_inset

, we choose an extra field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\sim\rep{6}$
\end_inset

.
 With these fields, one can write down the general superpotential 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{W}\supset\kappa_{1}\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\Sigma+m_{6}\Sigma\cdot\Sigma+\kappa_{2}\covp{\Sigma\Sigma}{6_{1}}\cdot\Sigma+\kappa_{3}\covp{\Sigma\Sigma}{6_{2}}\cdot\Sigma.
\]

\end_inset

 Such a superpotential generates a scalar potential as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
V_{36}=\kappa_{1}\covp{\bar{\varphi}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{6}\cdot\covp{\varphi\varphi^{\prime}}{6}+\kappa_{1}\covp{\bar{\varphi}\Sigma}{3}\cdot\covp{\varphi\bar{\Sigma}}{\bar{3}}+\kappa_{1}\covp{\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}\Sigma}{3}\cdot\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\Sigma}}{\bar{3}}\\
\kappa_{2}\covp{\Sigma\Sigma}{6_{1}}\covp{\bar{\Sigma}\bar{\Sigma}}{6_{1}}+\kappa_{3}\covp{\Sigma\Sigma}{6_{2}}\covp{\bar{\Sigma}\bar{\Sigma}}{6_{2}}+4m_{6}^{2}\covp{\Sigma\bar{\Sigma}}{1}+m^{2}\covp{\varphi\bar{\varphi}}{1}+m^{\prime2}\covp{\varphi^{\prime}\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}}{1},\label{eq:SUSY-V}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 where we have added the mass terms for triplets explicitly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can show that potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SUSY-V"

\end_inset

 is unable to produce the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 vacuum alignments.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SUSY-V"

\end_inset

 generate the vev as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Leading-vevs"

\end_inset

, then the first derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with respect to the fields at the critical point are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\bar{\varphi}_{1}}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\kappa_{1}v^{*}}{4\sqrt{3}}\left[\chi_{3}\bar{\chi}_{1}+\sqrt{2}\left(\bar{\chi}_{2}\bar{\phi}_{2}+\chi_{2}\phi_{1}\right)\right],\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\bar{\varphi}_{2}}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\kappa_{1}v^{*}}{4\sqrt{3}}\left[\chi_{3}\bar{\chi}_{2}+\sqrt{2}\bar{\chi}_{1}\bar{\phi}_{3}+2\left|v^{\prime}\right|^{2}+\sqrt{2}\chi_{1}\phi_{1}\right],\\
\left\langle \frac{\partial V}{\partial\bar{\varphi}_{3}}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\kappa_{1}v^{*}}{4\sqrt{3}}\left(\chi_{1}\bar{\chi}_{1}+\chi_{2}\bar{\chi}_{2}+2\phi_{1}\bar{\phi}_{1}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 The vanishing of the derivatives requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}=\chi_{2}=\phi_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SUSY-V"

\end_inset

 cannot produce the desired vevs.
 
\end_layout

